=head2 Formulae

I<[This section elaborates L<the corresponding entry in the RakuDoc specification|rakudoc:rakudoc_v2_specification.rakudoc#Formulae>]>

Implementors of renderers are B<I<not>> required to render the instructions (I<e.g.> the LaTeX code)
in a formula; it is acceptable for a renderer to render the contents
of a C<=formula> or C«F<>» in some other way than as a fully realized mathematical equation.

For example, the following two formulae:
=begin code :lang<text>
We will use the identity: F<\sum \frac{1}{n^{2}} = \frac{\pi^{2}}{6}>

...where the value of pi can be inferred from Euler’s Identity:

=formula e^{i\pi}+1=0
=end code

...may either be rendered “accurately”:
=begin nested
We will use the identity: F<\sum \frac{1}{n^{2}} = \frac{\pi^{2}}{6}>

...where the value of pi can be inferred from Euler’s Identity:

=for formula :!toc :caption('')
e^{i\pi}+1=0
=end nested

... or may be converted to a suitable Unicode approximation:

=begin nested
We will use the identity: ∑ 1/n² = 𝜋²/6

...where the value of pi can be inferred from Euler’s Identity:

eH<iπ> + 1 = 0

=end nested

... or may even left as raw LaTeX (perhaps with some kind of visual marker indicating
that it is unprocessed):

=begin nested
We will use the identity: I<U<V<\sum \frac{1}{n^{2}} = \frac{\pi^{2}}{6}>>>

... where the value of pi can be inferred from Euler’s Identity:

I<U<V<e^{i\pi}+1=0>>>
=end nested


=head2 Citations
=head3 Citation blocks

I<[This section elaborates L<the corresponding entry in the RakuDoc specification|rakudoc:rakudoc_v2_specification.rakudoc#Citation blocks>]>

The full citation dataset for each individual reference work is specified in
a C«citation» block, as structured textual data in any of the following notations:
CSL-JSON, CSL-YAML, CSL-Raku, RIS, MODS, BiBLaTeX, BibTeX, BibTeXML, or Medline/PubMed (XML or NBIB).
All of these formats are widely used citation-data-interchange standards, except for CSL-Raku,
which is just CSL-JSON/CSL-YAML data transposed into the native Raku syntax for a list of hashes.

For example:
=begin code :lang<rakudoc> :allow<I B>
I<=comment  Citation source data specified in B<CSL-Raku>>
=begin citation
    {
        note            => "Fields can be specified as key => value pairs"
        id              => "rakudoc-evo-chapter",
        type            => "chapter",
        title           => "The Evolution of RakuDoc",
        author          => [ { family => "Hainsworth", given => "Richard"   },
                             { family => "Mattijsen",  given => "Elizabeth" },
                             { family => "Conway",     given => "Damian"    },
                           ],
        editor          => [ { family => "Smith", given => "Jane" } ],
        container-title => "Modern Markup Systems",
        publisher       => "Butterfly Press",
        publisher-place => "Amsterdam",
        page            => "42-65",
        issued          => { date-parts => [[2024, 5, 12]] },
        ISBN            => "978-3-16-148410-0",
    },
    {
                   :note< Fields can also be specified as adverbial pairs >
                     :id< json-vs-xml-meta >
                   :type< article-journal >
                  :title< A Performance Analysis of JSON vs XML in Academic Metadata >
                 :author[ { family => "Doe", given => "John", ORCID => "0000-0001-2345-6789" } ]
        :container-title< Journal of Digital Humanities >
                 :volume( 12 )
                  :issue( 3 )
                   :page< 101-115 >
                    :DOI< 10.1000/jdh.2024.03.01 >
                 :issued{ date-parts => [[2024]] }
    }
=end citation

=end code
=begin code :lang<rakudoc> :allow<I B>
I<=comment  This citation data is in B<CSL-JSON> format>
=begin citation
    [
        {
                   "id": "mercurio2025",
                 "type": "book",
                "title": "The Morphological Beauty of Raku Grammars",
               "author": [ {"family": "Mercurio", "given": "Silvia"} ],
               "issued": {"date-parts": [[2025, 3, 14]]},
            "publisher": "Butterfly Press",
                 "ISBN": "978-1-2345-6789-0"
        }
    ]
=end citation

=end code
=begin code :lang<rakudoc> :allow<I B>
I<=comment  This citation data is B<CSL-YAML>>
=for citation
    - id:    starlight2024
      type:  article-journal
      title: "Asynchronous Concurrency: A Journey Through Raku Supplies"
      author:
          - family: Starlight
            given:  Orion
      container-title: "The Reactive Programmer's Quarterly"
      issued:
          date-parts: [[2024, 11]]
      volume: 12
      issue:  4
      page:   45-60

=end code
=begin code :lang<rakudoc> :allow<I B>
I<=comment  This citation is in B<BibLaTeX> format>
=citation  @article{zenraku2024,
               author = {Wall, Larry},
               title = {The Zen of Raku},
               journaltitle = {Journal of Camel Studies},
               date = {2024-05-12},
               volume = {42},
               number = {3},
               pages = {101-115},
               url = {https://example.org/raku},
               urldate = {2026-01-23}
           }

=end code
=begin code :lang<rakudoc> :allow<I B>
I<=comment  This citation is in B<BibTeXML> format>
=begin citation
    <bibtex:file xmlns:bibtex="http://bibtexml.sf.net/">
      <bibtex:entry id="mercurio2025">
        <bibtex:book>
          <bibtex:author>Silvia Mercurio</bibtex:author>
          <bibtex:title>The Morphological Beauty of Raku Grammars</bibtex:title>
          <bibtex:publisher>Butterfly Press</bibtex:publisher>
          <bibtex:year>2025</bibtex:year>
          <bibtex:month>March</bibtex:month>
          <bibtex:isbn>978-1-2345-6789-0</bibtex:isbn>
        </bibtex:book>
      </bibtex:entry>
    </bibtex:file>
=end citation

=end code
=begin code :lang<rakudoc> :allow<I B>
I<=comment  This is B<RIS> data>
=begin citation
    TY  - JOUR
    ID  - thorne2023
    AU  - Thorne, Alistair
    TI  - Optimization Strategies for MoarVM Bytecode
    JO  - Journal of Virtual Machine Design
    PY  - 2023/08/21/
    VL  - 9
    IS  - 2
    SP  - 210
    EP  - 235
    SN  - 1234-5678
    ER  -
=end citation

=end code
=begin code :lang<rakudoc> :allow<I B>
I<=comment  This is B<MODS>>
=begin citation
    <mods xmlns="http://www.loc.gov/mods/v3" ID="Vasiliev26">
        <titleInfo>
            <title>Functional Purity in a Multi-Paradigm World</title>
        </titleInfo>
        <name type="personal">
            <namePart type="given">Elena</namePart>
            <namePart type="family">Vasiliev</namePart>
            <role>
                <roleTerm type="text">author</roleTerm>
            </role>
        </name>
        <originInfo>
            <publisher>Deep Space Coding Collective</publisher>
            <dateIssued>2026</dateIssued>
        </originInfo>
        <typeOfResource>text</typeOfResource>
        <genre>technical report</genre>
    </mods>
=end citation

=end code
=begin code :lang<rakudoc> :allow<I B>
I<=comment This citation is in B<PubMed/Medline NBIB> format>
=citation
    PMID- 39876543
    STAT- Publisher
    DA  - 2025/08/15
    TI  - The Semantic Elegance of Raku Grammars.
    BTI - The Semantic Elegance of Raku Grammars
    AU  - Mercurio S
    LA  - eng
    PT  - Book
    PB  - Butterfly Press
    SN  - 978-1-2345-9876-0

=end code
=begin code :lang<rakudoc> :allow<I B V>
I<=comment This citation is in B<PubMed/Medline XML> format>
=citation
   <PubmedArticleSet>
     <PubmedArticle>
       <MedlineCitation Status="Publisher">
         <PMID Version="1">98765432</PMID>
         <Article PubModel="Print">
           <Journal>
             <ISSN IssnType="Print">1234-567X</ISSN>
             <JournalIssue>
               <Volume>14</Volume>
               <Issue>1</Issue>
               <PubDate>
                 <Year>2026</Year>
                 <Month>Jan</Month>
                 <Day>30</Day>
               </PubDate>
             </JournalIssue>
             <Title>International Journal of Perl and Raku</Title>
           </Journal>
           <ArticleTitle>Concurrent Processing in RakuDoc: A Performance Analysis.</ArticleTitle>
           <Pagination>
             <MedlinePgn>102-115</MedlinePgn>
           </Pagination>
           <AuthorList CompleteYN="Y">
             <Author ValidYN="Y">
               <LastName>Generic</LastName>
               <ForeName>A</ForeName>
             </Author>
             <Author ValidYN="Y">
               <LastName>Researcher</LastName>
               <ForeName>V<B></ForeName>
             </Author>
           </AuthorList>
           <Language>eng</Language>
           <PublicationTypeList>
             <PublicationType>Journal Article</PublicationType>
           </PublicationTypeList>
         </Article>
       </MedlineCitation>
     </PubmedArticle>
   </PubmedArticleSet>
=end code


=head2 Implied code and indentation

I<[This section elaborates L<the corresponding entry in the RakuDoc specification|rakudoc:rakudoc_v2_specification.rakudoc#Implied code and indentation>]>

Each block creates a virtual margin (at the column before its leading C<=>)
and that virtual margin extends B<I<only>> to the end of the block (I<i.e.> B<not> to the start
of the next named block).

Care must be taken with I<abbreviated> and I<extended> blocks where the block ends at the
next blank line.

=begin code :lang<RakuDoc>
=begin rakudoc
This is an ordinary paragraph

    While this is not an ordinary paragraph;
    it is a code block.

    =head Mumble mumble

    Surprisingly, this is a code block
        (with fancy indentation too)

This is just an ordinary paragraph.

=end rakudoc
=end code

The I<Surprisingly...> paragraph is a code block because each block only sets the virtual margin within that block,
and the C<=head> block terminates at the blank line immediately after
the C<=head> line, and before the apparent code block begins.
At which point, the virtual margin reverts to the previous virtual margin
set by the surrounding C<=begin rakudoc>...C<=end rakudoc> block.

The current virtual margin terminates at the end of the block whose opener set it,
and not at the start of the next block that sets a virtual margin.
In other words, the virtual margin is a local feature of each individual block, not a collective feature
of the entire document, and therefore a block’s virtual margin always ends at the end of the block itself
(and reverts at that point to the virtual margin of the surrounding block, if any).

Which means:
=begin code :lang<RakuDoc>
=begin rakudoc
This is an ordinary paragraph

    While this is not
    This is a code block

    =head Mumble mumble

    This IS also a code block
       because the preceding =head's virtual margin ended
       at the end of the preceding =head block, which was
       at the preceding blank line. So the virtual margin for
       this implicit block is the virtual margin of the surrounding
       C<=begin rakudoc ... =end rakudoc> block. This block is indented
       relative to that C<=rakudoc block>'s virtual margin, so it's
       a code block.

This is a para block
    (with fancy indentation too, because the indentation of first line alone
     determines whether an implicit block is a C<=para> or a C<=code> block,
     and all subsequent lines, regardless of their indentation, become part
     of that block ... until the end of the implicit block, which occurs at
     the next blank line or the next explicit RakuDoc block or directive.)

=end rakudoc
=end code

And if, instead, you wanted the block straight after the C<=head> to be
an implicit paragraph block (I<i.e.> not an implicit code block),
you'd write it:

=begin code :lang<RakuDoc> :allow<B>
=begin rakudoc
This is an ordinary paragraph

    While this is not
    This is a code block

    B<=begin section>

    =head Mumble mumble

    This is a para block, NOT a code block
       because the virtual margin for this implicit block
       is the virtual margin of the surrounding
       =begin section ... =end section block.
       The first line of this implicit block is NOT indented
       relative to that =section block's virtual margin,
       so it's a para block.

    B<=end section>

This is a para block too...because its first line is not indented
   relative to the virtual margin of the current =begin rakudoc ... =end rakudoc block.

=end rakudoc
=end code


=head Metadata
=head2 Instructions with side effects
=head3 Display and metadata

I<[This section elaborates L<the corresponding entry in the RakuDoc specification|rakudoc:rakudoc_v2_specification.rakudoc#Metadata>]>

Markup codes may contain only display text or may contain
a mix of display and meta information. This section clarifies these groups.

If a markup code may contain both display text and meta information, the character C<|> is used
to delimit the two components. In order to use C<|> inside a display text, it must be escaped (C<\|>) or
specified as an entity (C«E<VERTICAL LINE>»).

=head4 Display only codes

The following codes may I<only> contain display text:
=begin code :allow<B R V> :lang<RakuDoc>
BV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
CV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
HV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
IV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
JV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
KV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
NV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
OV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
RV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
SV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
TV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
UV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
VV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
WV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT> V« >»
=end code

=head4 Metadata and (optional) display text

The following codes may (and, in some cases, must) contain both a display text
and some kind of metadata.

=begin code :allow<B R V> :lang<RakuDoc>
AV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT > V« | » R<METADATA=ALIAS-NAME>            >
DV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT > V« | » R<METADATA=SYNONYMS>              >
ΔV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT > V« | » R<METADATA=VERSION-ETC>           >
EV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT > V« | » R<METADATA=HTML/UNICODE-ENTITIES> >
FV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT > V« | » R<METADATA=LATEX-FORM>            >
LV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT > V« | » R<METADATA=TARGET-URI>            >
MV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT > V« | » R<METADATA=WHATEVER>              >
PV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT > V« | » R<METADATA=REPLACEMENT-URI>       >
XV«< » R<DISPLAY-TEXT > V« | » R<METADATA=INDEX-ENTRY>           >
=end code

The markup codes C<A>, C<E>, C<F>, C<L>, and C<P> may be specified B<without> a display text,
in which case the specification permits the renderer to
provide an automatic rendering if the metadata component fails to produce a renderable result.
If an explicit display text is provided (I<i.e.> to the left of a C<|>),
that text overrides the default alternate rendering.

=head4 Metadata only

=begin code :allow<V R> :lang<RakuDoc>
QV«< » R<METADATA=CITATION REFERENCES> >
ZV«< » R<METADATA=COMMENT> >
=end code

The quotation code C<Q<> > has a semicolon list akin to a metadata list, which is
replaced in the rendered text with properly styled citations.

The comment code C<Z<> > is intended not to have a display text so the contents of a comment
can be considered as pure metadata.


=head Summary of RakuDoc syntax

=begin table2 :caption<Directives> :toc
    =row :header
        =cell Directive
        =cell Specifies
    =row
        =cell C<=alias>
        =cell Define a RakuDoc macro
    =row
        =cell C<=begin>
        =cell Start of an explicitly terminated block
    =row
        =cell C<=column>
        =cell Start a new column in a procedural table
    =row
        =cell C<=config>
        =cell Block-scoped modifications to a block or markup instruction
    =row
        =cell C<=counter>
        =cell Block-scoped reconfiguration of a counter
    =row
        =cell C<=document>
        =cell Change the default for document level options
    =row
        =cell C<=end>
        =cell Explicit termination of a C<=begin> block
    =row
        =cell C<=finish>
        =cell No ambient blocks after this point
    =row
        =cell C<=for>
        =cell Start of an implicitly (blank-line) terminated block
    =row
        =cell C<=place>
        =cell Place into the document some text loaded from, or generated by, a URI
    =row
        =cell C<=row>
        =cell Start a new row in a procedural table
=end table2

=begin section
=config C :allow<R>
=begin table2 :caption<Blocks> :toc
    =row :header
        =cell Block typename
        =cell Specifies
    =row
        =cell C<=cell>
        =cell Contents of a table cell, only valid in a procedural table context
    =row
        =cell C<=citation>
        =cell Specify a list of citation datasets in one of several standard citation markup languages
    =row
        =cell C<=code>
        =cell Verbatim pre-formatted sample source code
    =row
        =cell C<=input>
        =cell Pre-formatted sample input
    =row
        =cell C<=output>
        =cell Pre-formatted sample output
    =row
        =cell C<=comment>
        =cell Content to be ignored by all renderers
    =row
        =cell C<=head>
        =cell First-level heading
    =row
        =cell C<=headR<N>>
        =cell Nth-level heading
    =row
        =cell C<=defn>
        =cell Definition of a term
    =row
        =cell C<=item>
        =cell First-level list item
    =row
        =cell C<=itemR<N>>
        =cell Nth-level list item
    =row
        =cell C<=nested>
        =cell Nest block contents within the current context
    =row
        =cell C<=para>
        =cell Ordinary paragraph
    =row
        =cell C<=rakudoc>
        =cell No "ambient" blocks inside
    =row
        =cell C<=section>
        =cell Defines a lexical scope within the document
    =row
        =cell C<=pod>
        =cell Legacy equivalent to C<=rakudoc> (use is deprecated)
    =row
        =cell C<=table>
        =cell Visual or procedural table
    =row
        =cell C<=formula>
        =cell Render content as a LaTeX formula
    =row
        =cell C<=data>
        =cell Raku data section
    =row
        =cell C<=R<NAMED>>
        =cell Semantic blocks (C<=SYNOPSIS>, C<=TITLE>, I<etc.>)
    =row
        =cell C<=R<CustomName>>
        =cell User-defined block (must have mixed-case name)
=end table2
=end section

=begin section
=config C :allow<R>
=begin table2 :caption<Metadata options> :toc
    =row :header
        =cell Metadata option
        =cell Blocks applied to
        =cell Description
    =row
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(4) :align<top>
            C<:allow>

        =column
            =cell C<=code>
            =cell C<=input>
            =cell C<=output>
            =cell C<=table>
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(4) :align<top>
            Allow specific mark-up codes in otherwise verbatim blocks

    =row
        =cell C<:id>
        =cell all blocks
        =cell Specify the anchor for a block

    =row
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(8) :align<top>
            C<:toc>

        =column
            =cell C<=para>
            =cell C<=nested>
            =cell C<=code>
            =cell C<=input>
            =cell C<=output>
            =cell C<=table>
            =cell C<=formula>
            =cell C<=place>

        =column
            =for cell :row-span(8) :align<top>
            Include content or caption in the Table of Contents

    =row
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(4) :align<top>
            C<:!toc>

        =column
            =cell SEMANTIC block
            =cell Custom block
            =cell C<=headR<N>>
            =cell C<=numheadR<N>>

        =column
            =for cell :row-span(4) :align<top>
            Do not include content or caption in the Table of Contents

    =row
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(2) :align<top>
            C<:headlevel>

        =column
            =cell All blocks
            =cell (but typically for para-ish blocks)

        =column
            =for cell :row-span(2) :align<top>
            Override the automatic level of the block type within a Table of Contents

    =row
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(9) :align<top>
            C<:caption>

        =column
            =cell SEMANTIC block
            =cell Custom block
            =cell C<=nested>
            =cell C<=code>
            =cell C<=input>
            =cell C<=output>
            =cell C<=table>
            =cell C<=formula>
            =cell C<=place>

        =column
            =for cell :row-span(9) :align<top>
            Caption to be associated with a block in the Table of Contents
    =row
        =cell C<:hidden>
        =cell SEMANTIC block
        =cell Remove block from rendered text and from Table of Contents (use C<P<semantic: ...>> to inject elsewhere)

    =row
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(4) :align<top>
            C<:header>

        =column
            =cell C<=table> (procedural semantics only)
            =cell C<=cell>
            =cell C<=row> directive
            =cell C<=column> directive

        =column
            =for cell :row-span(4) :align<top>
            Specify rows, columns, or cells to be rendered as column headers in a table

    =row
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(4) :align<top>
            C<:label>

        =column
            =cell C<=table> (procedural semantics only)
            =cell C<=cell>
            =cell C<=row> directive
            =cell C<=column> directive

        =column
            =for cell :row-span(4) :align<top>
            Specify rows, columns, or cells to be rendered as labels (row headers) in a table

    =row
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(4) :align<top>
            C<:align<R<ALIGNMENTS>>>

        =column
            =cell C<=table> (procedural semantics only)
            =cell C<=cell>
            =cell C<=row> directive
            =cell C<=column> directive

        =column
            =for cell :row-span(4) :align<top>
            Specify how cell contents are to be vertically and/or horizontally aligned

    =row
            =cell C<:row-span(R<HEIGHT>)>
            =cell C<=cell>
            =cell Specify how many rows a single cell should span in a procedural table

    =row
            =cell C<:column-span(R<WIDTH>)>
            =cell C<=cell>
            =cell Specify how many columns a single cell should span in a procedural table

    =row
            =cell C<:span(R<WIDTH>, R<HEIGHT>)>
            =cell C<=cell>
            =cell A shorthand for C<:column-span(R<WIDTH>) :row-span(R<HEIGHT>)>

    =row
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(10) :align<top>
            C<:delta>

        =column
            =cell C<=table>
            =cell C<=formula>
            =cell C<=nested>
            =cell C<=code>
            =cell C<=input>
            =cell C<=output>
            =cell C<=headR<N>>
            =cell C<=numheadR<N>>
            =cell SEMANTIC block
            =cell Custom block

        =column
            =for cell :row-span(10) :align<top>
            Developer information associated with a block
    =row
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(2)
            C<:bullet<R<CHAR>>>
        =column
            =cell C<=item>
            =cell C<=itemR<N>>
        =column
            =for cell :row-span(2)
            Replace the default bullet with one or more characters, or entities specified with C<E< >>

=end table2
=end section

=begin section
=config C :allow<R V>
=begin table2 :caption<Markup instructions> :toc

    =row :header
        =cell Markup instruction
        =cell Specifies
    =row
        =cell C<A<...|...>>
        =cell Alias to be replaced by contents of the specified C<=alias> directive
              (C<A<R<alt text> | R<aliasname>>>)
    =row
        =cell C<B<...>>
        =cell Basis/focus of sentence (typically rendered bold)
    =row
        =cell C<C<...>>
        =cell Code (typically rendered fixed-width)
    =row
        =cell C<D<...>>
        =cell Definition inline (C<D<R<term being defined> | R<synonym1>; R<synonym2>>>)
    =row
        =cell C<Δ<...|...;...>>
        =cell Delta note (C<Δ<R<visible text> | R<version>; R<notification text>>>)
    =row
        =cell C<EV«<»...|...;...>>
        =cell Entity (HTML or Unicode) description (C<EV«<»R<entity1>; R<entity2>; R<multi>,R<glyph>;...>>)
    =row
        =cell C<F<...|...>>
        =cell Inline content for a formula (C<F<R<alt text> | R<LaTeX notation>>>)
    =row
        =cell C<G<...>>
        =cell I<(This markup code is not yet defined, but is reserved for future use)>
    =row
        =cell C<H<...>>
        =cell High text (typically rendered superscript)
    =row
        =cell C<I<...>>
        =cell Important content (typically rendered in italics)
    =row
        =cell C<J<...>>
        =cell Junior text (typically rendered subscript)
    =row
        =cell C<K<...>>
        =cell Keyboard input (typically rendered fixed-width)
    =row
        =cell C<L<...|...>>
        =cell Link (C<L<R<display text> | R<destination URI>>>)
    =row
        =cell C<M<...|..,..;...>>
        =cell Markup extra (C<M<R<display text> | R<functionality>; R<param>,R<sub-type>;R<...>>>)
    =row
        =cell C<N<...>>
        =cell Note (not rendered inline, but made visible in some way: footnote, sidenote, pop-up, I<etc.>))
    =row
        =cell C<O<...>>
        =cell Struck-out content
    =row
        =cell C<P<...|...>>
        =cell Placement link (C<P< R<alt text> | R<source URI> >>)
    =row
        =cell C«Q<...>»
        =cell Marker citing one or more bibliographic datasets via identifiers
              with possible text annotations (C<QV«<» R<ID1> ; R<ID2>, R<text>; R<etc.> V«>»>)
    =row
        =cell C<RV«<»...V«>»>
        =cell Replaceable component or metasyntax
    =row
        =cell C<S<...>>
        =cell Space characters to be preserved
    =row
        =cell C<T<...>>
        =cell Terminal output (typically rendered fixed-width)
    =row
        =cell C<U<...>>
        =cell Unusual content (typically rendered with underlining)
    =row
        =cell C<VV«<»...V«>»>
        =cell Verbatim (internal markup instructions ignored)
    =row
        =cell C<W<...>>
        =cell Weighty content (typically rendered with small caps)
    =row
        =cell C<X<...|..,..;...>>
        =cell Index entry (C<X< R<display text> | R<entry>,R<subentry> ; ...>>)
    =row
        =cell C<Y<...>>
        =cell I<(This markup code is not yet defined, but is reserved for future use)>
    =row
        =cell C<Z<...>>
        =cell Zero-width comment (contents never rendered)
    =row
=end table2
=end section
=begin table2 :caption<:form components> :toc
=row :header
	=cell Field
	=cell Meaning
	=cell C«:lc» or informal shortcut
